<H3> <TI>   Vondra Cited on International `Failure' in B-H </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vondra Cited on International `Failure' in B-H </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004085294 Prague CTK in English 1444 GMT 19 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2004085294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague April 19 (CTK) -- It is in the interest of 
the Czech Republic and the whole international community that 
the maximum be done to prevent such situations like the one 
which has recently occurred in Bosnia, and to prevent mainly 
Serbian politicians from further ignoring UN resolutions, 
Alexandr Vondra said today. 
  "The recent developments are very disturbing," said Vondra, 
Czech deputy foreign minister. 
  As a member of the UN Security Council, which has met to 
discuss the situation in the Bosnian enclave of Gorazde, the 
Czech Republic has to push for an agreement within this 
institution, Vondra said. 
  The UN should try to do more, and everybody capable of 
positively influencing the Bosnian situation should take a more 
active part in the settlement of the crisis. "To a certain 
extent, it is probably also a failure of the international 
community," Vondra stated. 
  He said he believed that the Czech Republic had made a 
considerable effort to help solve the problem. It had taken an 
active part in discussions within the UN Security Council, and 
assisted in keeping the peace. The number of Czech UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Force] soldiers stationed in the former Yugoslavia 
was now a thousand, many more in comparison with the country's 
population than the number of soldiers from most big powers and 
other influential European countries. Czech humanitarian aid 
was not negligible either, Vondra said. 

</TEXT>

