<H3> <TI>   Polls Show Preference for ODS </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Polls Show Preference for ODS </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1604151794 Prague CTK in English 1824 GMT 15 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1604151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 15 (CTK) -- If parliamentary 
elections were to take place now, they would be won by the Civic 
Democratic Party (ODS) with 30.7 percent of the vote, according 
to a poll of 1,546 Czechs taken on April 1-10 by the Center for 
Empirical Research (STEM). 
  The second strongest party would be the Czech Social 
Democratic Party (CSSD) with 15.7 percent, while third would be 
the coalition Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA) with 12.7 percent. 
  The former Left Bloc coalition would receive 9.1 percent, 
and 
6.9 percent would vote for the Communist Party of Bohemia and 
Moravia (KSCM). 
  With 5.3 percent, the government coalition Christian 
Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL) would 
narrowly receive more than the five percent of votes needed for 
entry to parliament. The Christian Democratic Party (KDS), also 
a coalition party, would receive only 0.6 percent. 
  Parties on the rise include the Assembly for the Republic 
(SPR- RSC) with 3.8 percent and the Free Democrats (SD, formerly 
OH) with 3.4 percent of votes. 
  The Green Party would receive 2.2 percent and the Liberal 
and 
Social Union 1.2 percent. 
  Seventy seven percent of respondents would take part in 
elections, a figure which rises to 92 percent among ODS 
supporters and 83 percent of ODA supporters. At the other end 
of the scale, 62 percent of Green Party supporters and 61 
percent of SPR-RSC supporters would take part. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

