<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   IVVM Survey Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IVVM Survey Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1904124594 Prague CTK in English 0926 GMT 19 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1904124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 19 (CTK) -- Seventy-one percent of 
people in the Czech Republic would go to the polls if elections 
to the Czech Parliament were held now, according to a poll 
conducted by the Institute for Public Opinion Research (IVVM) on 
March 28-April 6. 
  The poll of 1,544 respondents with the right to vote 
revealed 
that 37 percent of the electorate were certain they would vote, 
34 percent said they probably would, and eight percent said 
"probably not." Ten percent of those surveyed replied with a 
"resolute no" and 11 percent had not decided. The higher the 
level of education, the less frequent was the answer "I do not 
know" and more frequent the intention to go to the polls, the 
survey showed. 
  Twenty-eight percent of the electorate would vote Czech 
Premier Vaclav Klaus's Civic Democratic Party (ODS), 12 percent 
Milos Zeman's Czech Social Democratic Party (CSSD), and 11 
percent Deputy Premier Jan Kalvoda's Civic Democratic Alliance 
(ODA). 
  More than five percent of those polled supported the 
Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSCM) and the Assembly 
for the Republic-Czechoslovak Republican Party (SPR-RSC). Four 
percent were in favor of the government coalition Christian 
Democratic Union- Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL). 
  The Left Bloc (LB), former Czechoslovak Foreign Minister 
Jiri 
Dienstbier's Free Democrats (SD), the Green Party (SZ), the 
Farmers' Party (ZS), the government coalition Christian 
Democratic Party (KDS), and the Czech-Moravian Center Party 
(CMSS) all received less than four percent. 
  Twenty-three percent of the voters did not know which party 
they would support. 
  Compared with last month's figures, the ODS has dropped in 
popularity and the CSSD, the KSCM, and the SPR-RSC strengthened 
their positions. 

</TEXT>

