<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Horn Meets With Moravcik </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Horn Meets With Moravcik </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004085994 Budapest MTI in English 1849 GMT 19 Apr 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2004085994 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, 19 April (MTI) -- Opposition Hungarian 
Socialist Party (MSZP) Chairman Gyula Horn saw Slovak Prime 
Minister Jozef Moravcik for over an hour in Bratislava today. 
The meeting during Horn's stay in Dunajska Streda was requested 
by the Slovaks. 
  Horn told MTI, "I explained what the Hungarian Socialists 
mean by historic reconciliation, how old grievances are to be 
set aside and history should be for historians rather than 
politicians. I told the prime minister that we want to take 
confidence-building steps in this direction." 
  "A basic treaty is vital for relations. If the MSZP enters 
government after the May elections, Hungary would still sign the 
treaty. Moravcik spoke of some fear among Slovaks. They hope 
the basic treaty will fix the inviolabity of borders," Horn said. 
  The MSZP chairman said the basic treaty could eliminate 
fear. 
"Of course, all this is closely connected with what the basic 
treaty should declare on national minorities. I told the prime 
minister that the Hungarian nation's sense of solidarity with 
ethnic Hungarians beyond the border is natural. Hungary's 
efforts for a European agreement protecting national minorities 
to be signed is also understandable," Horn said. 
  "It is part of the basic treaty that Hungary would promote 
the economic prosperity of ethnic Hungarians in Slovakia, and 
welcome their cultural and administrative autonomy. Of course, 
reality should always be kept in view," Horn said. 

</TEXT>

