<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Program's Financial Position Reviewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Program's Financial Position Reviewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004085194 Prague CTK in English 1741 GMT 19 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2004085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava April 19 (CTK) -- Slovakia needs 17 
billion crowns (about 515 million USD) to complete construction 
of the nuclear power plant at Mochovce, an official at the 
Economy Ministry said today. 
  The plant's first two reactors, which are 90 percent 
complete, were to have started operating by 1995, but now it 
appears they will not be ready until 2000. 
  Work on the plant was interrupted last year due to a lack of 
money and the breakup of its supply system. The Economy 
Ministry and Slovak industry representatives are negotiating 
conditions for a loan to pay sub-contractors. 
  Those from the Czech Republic who participated in the 
plant's 
construction, mainly through the Skoda Plzen engineering group, 
are owed 2.1 billion Slovak crowns. 
  The Economy Ministry's Imrich Szitas said it appeared that 
Russia, the plant's likely future supplier of nuclear fuel, 
would provide a loan of 450 million USD. Preliminary talks 
between Economics Minister Peter Magvasi and Russian officials 
suggest that Slovak imports of fuel would be paid for with 
exports of Slovak goods. 
  Talks are also being conducted with the European Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) and a consortium of 
Electricite de France and Bayernwerk of Germany on a possible 
loan of 1.3 billion marks that would be paid through supplies of 
electricity. 
  Szitas denied that the EBRD made a loan conditional on the 
shutting down of a reactor at another Slovak nuclear plant, 
located in Jaslovske Bohunice, West Slovakia. It will be shut 
down once the Mochovce plant is completed, he said. 
  The entire plant in Jaslovske Bohunice is undergoing changes 
to increase safety in a gradual process that is to be completed 
in 1997, Szitas noted. 

</TEXT>

