<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central European Presidents Meet in Lityomysl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central European Presidents Meet in Lityomysl </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Havel Denies Tension With Klaus </H4>

<F P=102> AU1804140794 Prague CTK in English 1712 GMT 16 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1804140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Litomysl, East Bohemia, April 16 (CTK) -- Czech 
President Vaclav Havel today refuted journalists' speculations 
that the absence of Premier Vaclav Klaus at a joint dinner of 
the seven Central European presidents on Friday [15 April] was 
caused by the tension allegedly existing between him and Klaus. 
  Havel told CTK at a press conference at the close of the 
summit that, in a telephone call with him on Thursday, Klaus 
excused himself, arguing that he was not quite well and had to 
prepare for a trip to South America. 
  "I have no reason whatsoever to look for a different 
background to this," Havel said, adding that none of the 
presidents commented on Klaus' absence because none of them were 
accompanied by a premier. 
  Journalists present considered Klaus' absence to be one of 
the most interesting aspects of the summit. Speculations were 
being spread whether a mere personal problem, probably 
concerning the division of powers, was behind Klaus's gestures 
or whether another, deeper meaning should be searched for. 
  First Deputy Foreign Minister Alexandr Vondra and Parliament 
Chairman Milan Uhde were also invited to attend the meeting. 
Uhde excused himself because of a very important meeting in 
Velka Bites, south Moravia, Havel's spokesman Ladislav Spacek 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

