<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central European Presidents Meet in Lityomysl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central European Presidents Meet in Lityomysl </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Havel Comments on Summit </H4>

<F P=102> AU1804131794 Prague CTK in English 1726 GMT 16 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1804131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Litomysl, East Bohemia, April 16 (CTK) -- The 
states whose presidents met at the Litomysl summit do not feel 
they are a political or geopolitical body that should play a 
role or even be a link between Eastern and Western Europe, 
President Vaclav Havel said today. 
  The seven Central European presidents met because their 
countries shared many concerns, but because they wanted to be 
considered as distinct from other parts of Europe, he said at a 
press conference at the end of the summit. [sentence as received] 
  Havel said the presidents should meet as frequently as 
possible, though not necessarily all of them together. 
Groupings could depend on the matter discussed, he proposed. 
  If it was felt that some president who should have 
participated was overlooked, "we shall see him next time we 
meet", Havel said, probably in an allusion to press comment that 
the Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro should have been 
invited. 
  Havel informed reporters Austrian President Thomas Klestil 
had invited to a future meeting in Alpbach which the Swiss 
President Otto Stich might also attend. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

