<H3> <TI>   Situation in Gorazde -- 21 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Situation in Gorazde -- 21 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    TANJUG: Gorazde Not `Destroyed' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2104125394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1101 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2104125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Scepan Aleksic] </F>
  [Excerpt] Serb positions near Gorazde, 21 Apr (TANJUG) -- 
Gorazde is neither destroyed nor devastated and any comparison 
with the flattened town of Mostar or -- as the Muslim propaganda 
likes to present it -- with Vukovar is in complete contrast with 
the real situation. A group of journalists who visited the Serb 
infantry units on the front line had the opportunity to see the 
extent of the deception used by Muslim radio in Sarajevo and the 
Western media, which insist that Gorazde is in flames and ruins. 
There is a clear view of Gorazde from the Biserna hill on the 
right bank of the Drina river about 800 meters from the town 
center. 
  On the river's left bank several floors of the Gradina Hotel 
are burned down. Several windows on one of the highest 
buildings in the town center are blackened with smoke. The 
glass roof on the sports hall is broken. Roofs on several 
buildings have been damaged. Minor damage, most likely from 
gunfire, can be seen on some buildings, and that is all. True, 
there are very few people in the streets and people run when 
crossing the bridges. But there is no evidence of any corpses 
in the streets, as reported by Muslim radio and the Western 
media that has been using it as its source. [Passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

