<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Situation in Gorazde -- Apr 20 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Situation in Gorazde -- Apr 20 </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UNPROFOR Still Not Arrived </H4>

<F P=102> LD2004171194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1644 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004171194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Zvornik, Bratunac, 20 Apr (TANJUG) -- UN 
peacekeepers and a medical team have not yet succeeded in 
entering Gorazde, although the Serbian side has done everything 
in its power to ensure that this mission is accomplished, 
TANJUG's correspondent learned from republic of Srpska army 
sources this evening. The same sources specified that republic 
of Srpska president Radovan Karadzic and UN special envoy 
Yasushi Akashi agreed on this mission on Sunday. It was 
allegedly agreed that 100 UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] 
members and a 60-member medical team should go to Gorazde. 
However, the Serbian side was not told about the reasons for 
delaying the start of the mission; it was told that the military 
and medical contingent could arrive in Gorazde tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

