<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Says Serbs `Ready for Talks' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Says Serbs `Ready for Talks' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004180694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1709 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004180694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 20 Apr (TANJUG) -- Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the republic of Srpska, today welcomed British 
Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd's statement that the peace 
process in Bosnia would be renewed soon. In an official 
statement -- TANJUG received a copy of the text -- Karadzic said 
that "the Serbian side is ready for talks, but only on the basis 
of equality." 
  "This means that the international community must make a 
step 
forward in connection with the sanctions, imposed on the entire 
Serbian nation, before any talks could start," stressed 
Karadzic. He specified that the international community must 
ensure that this time the Muslims negotiate with good 
intentions. The Muslim military offensives will no longer be 
tolerated and the Serbs will respond to them with resolve. In 
this context Karadzic reiterated that the Muslims caused the 
latest clashes by launching an offensive from Gorazde a month 
ago and that "they remembered Gorazde was a safe area only when 
they suffered a setback in their offensive." The international 
community should have inquired what a Muslim army division in 
full combat gear was doing in a safe area, said Karadzic. 
  In order for an "agreement to be likely," as suggested by 
Hurd, the international community ought to "stop playing the 
Muslim game of war and peace" and it must oppose the Muslim 
right to veto every peace plan which had already been agreed 
with the European Union and the United Nations. "The 
international community ought to make it quite clear to the 
Muslims that their impossible ambition to control the entire 
Bosnia, as a method of sabotaging peace, will not longer be 
tolerated," said Karadzic. "Peace will come to Bosnia only when 
the international community accepts the obvious truth that the 
Serbs have the right to self-determination just like the other 
ethnic communities," said Karadzic, concluding that "immoral and 
totally counterproductive sanctions and threats of force cannot 
conceal this obvious truth." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

