<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Issues Statement on Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Issues Statement on Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004172294 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1600 
GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2004172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Foreign Ministry issued a statement today 
regarding developments in the situation around the Bosnian town 
of Gorazde. The statement recalls the Bulgarian viewpoint 
stated on 12 April 1994, which expressed alarm regarding the 
possible development of a chain reaction of military actions and 
an escalation of the conflict. Unfortunately, this chain 
reaction is now a fact. 
  The Bulgarian Foreign Ministry once again appeals to the 
warring parties to halt their military actions and show greater 
flexibility and realism in the search for solutions. A 
compromise on Bosnia-Herzegovina's present and future can be 
found only at the negotiating table, only within a broader 
European framework, with active cooperation and coordination 
between the United States, the European Union, and Russia, and 
with the assistance of the United Nations. 
  Bulgaria is ready to play an active part in the discussion 
of 
any international plan leading to the attainment of these goals; 
it is also ready to make its diplomatic and political 
contribution toward halting the bloodshed. 
  The Foreign Ministry is glad to welcome the initiative for a 
summit meeting of representatives of the Russia, the United 
States, and the European Union on the situation in Bosnia, and 
hopes that a solution to this conflict may be found within the 
framework of this meeting. The holding of such a meeting in a 
country in the region in the immediate vicinity of the conflict 
will constitute a clear signal that the participants in the 
meeting are ready to commit themselves to an even greater extent 
to restoring stability, security, and cooperation in the 
Balkans, the Foreign Ministry statement says in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

