<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Energy Supply Unaffected by Miners' Strike </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Energy Supply Unaffected by Miners' Strike </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104093294 Warsaw PAP in Polish 0851 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104093294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 21 Apr--A 48-hour strike in all lignite 
mines, organized by the Solidarity trade unions, began at 0700 
hours. Four hours after the protest started, Miroslaw 
Maksymiuk. of the national load-dispatching unit [krajowa 
dyspozycja mocy], told a PAP journalist: "Nothing is happening. 
We are meeting the entire demand for electricity. If it stops 
coming from lignite-fired power stations, we still have other 
sources of energy." 
  The extraction and consumption of lignite dropped in recent 
years from 73.8 million tonnes in 1988 to 66.8 million in 1992. 
Power and heat and power-generating plants located near lignite 
mines are using approximately 98 percent of all extracted 
lignite. 

</TEXT>

