<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Answers Questions on Political Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus Answers Questions on Political Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004171694 Prague LIDOVE NOVINY in Czech 15 Apr 94 pp 1, 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU2004171694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague LIDOVE NOVINY </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus by Eva </F>
Martinkova; place and date not given: "Some Parties Are Playing 
False Cards"] 
  [Text] [Martinkova] In your view, what is the objective 
of the Litomysl meeting of presidents? 
  [Klaus] This provides yet another means of communication 
with neighboring countries. We desire this communication, we 
are striving for it, and we are pleased that it is going to 
happen. Moreover, the meeting has another important 
aspect--breaking down the incessant polarization of the world 
into West and East. The fact that the presidents of Austria and 
Germany will also be there is, I think, a step in the right 
direction. 
  [Martinkova] In the wake of Wednesday's [13 April] 
government session, do the ambiguities within the coalition over 
the jurisdiction of the higher territorial units still persist? 
  [Klaus] There is no fundamental dispute among the coalition 
parties in the actual issue of jurisdiction. When we begin to 
discuss whether the new regions may conclude international 
treaties or announce their own taxes or smog alert levels, or 
build their own theaters or galleries, any overpoliticized 
dispute will evaporate. The government coalition ministers, in 
closed ranks, are looking for ways to define jurisdiction. The 
problems lie somewhere else. In the political game, that is 
being played beyond the matter-of-fact element of this issue. 
  I repeat: This is not a matter-of-fact dispute. Some parties 
are still pulling false cards from their sleeves. I would hope 
that they do not play with them. 
  [Martinkova] The unemployment rate in the Czech Republic is 
one of the lowest in the world. Apparently, only Luxembourg, 
Japan, and New Zealand are doing better. Nevertheless, the 
government is often the target of criticism because of this. 
Can we in the Czech Republic talk about false employment, 
employment that interferes with natural economic relations? 
  [Klaus] Unemployment in our country is the way it is; no one 
is holding it back or speeding it up. Each month the government 
awaits with anticipation the figures on its movement, without in 
any way attempting to manipulate it. Its low level is a major 
success, which, on the other hand, is the subject of various 
worst-case scenarios and elaborations on the artificial curbing 
of unemployment. What I mean is the criticism from some 
economists from the postcommunist countries. However, even 
Western states are a little envious of our low unemployment 
rate. The current level is a consequence of our economy's 
exceptionally high absorption capability. For example, in the 
Louny District, where the unemployment level is one of the 
highest--it is touching 8 percent--there are about 3,000 
unemployed. However, three years ago, 7,000 people lost their 
jobs due to the collapse of the large agricultural enterprises. 
Where are they? In new jobs. 
  [Martinkova] You say that the enterprise sphere is the trade 
unionists' domain, not collective bargaining at the 
macroeconomic level. The Maastricht Treaty, however, even takes 
into consideration supranational collective bargaining within 
the framework of the European Union. 
  [Klaus] I have never made a secret of my criticism of the 
Maastricht Treaty. The social democratic authors who 
participated in drafting it have left their mark in certain 
points. The social sphere is one of them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9151 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu078aa_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-078 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Crans Montana Forum Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Crans Montana Forum Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Iliescu, 'Arafat, Peres on Talks </H4>

<F P=102> AU2104145694 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1300 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2104145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>
<F P=105>  Romanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] A meeting between Romanian President 
Mr. Ion Iliescu, PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat, and Israeli Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres took place at Cotroceni Palace. The 
meeting concluded a short while ago. 
  Before that, another meeting took place at noon between PLO 
Leader Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres. 
According to ROMPRES, the head of the Israeli diplomacy said the 
following, at the end of the meeting: The negotiations are not 
yet over. For the time being, there is nothing to announce yet. 
Asked whether he is optimistic, Shim'on Peres said, quote: I 
am always optimistic. This optimism is also shared by Yasir 
'Arafat. [no reference to close of quotation as heard] 
  We have now received from our correspondents the statements 
made by the three participants in today's talks at Cotroceni 
Palace. First, the statement made by President Ion Iliescu. 
  [Begin Iliescu recording] We will not make any special 
statements now. Another meeting will take place at 1700, 
whereby Chairman 'Arafat and Mr. Peres will briefly report on 
the stage of the negotiations conducted last night and this 
morning and the prospects for finalizing certain positive and 
concrete aspects related to the ongoing negotiations in Cairo. 
I would like to point out the political significance of these 
meetings and talks in Bucharest as well as the effort and 
political determination of the two leaders to achieve something. 
If one usually talks about courage and heroism in the military 
struggle, I believe that one needs no less courage and heroism 
to build peace, overcome conflicts, and struggle against the 
trend of hatred and immobility accumulated over a long period of 
time. I believe that this was a display of true courage from 
the politicians of both Israel and the Palestinian side. What 
both Chairman 'Arafat and Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin and 
Minister Peres are striving to achieve these days is an act of 
courage, which we appreciate as such. I believe it is in the 
interest of the international community to support these 
realistic and brave politicians in their efforts. [end 
recording] 
  [Announcer] Then, Mr. Yasir 'Arafat said: 
  [Begin 'Arafat recording, in English with superimposed 
translation into Romanian] We have to thank His Excellency, the 
president, for his contribution to the progress of the peace 
talks, by arranging the meeting between myself and His 
Excellency Mr. Shim'on Peres. We hope to enjoy your 
hospitality, in Bucharest this time, to continue our talks and 
negotiations, so that we can finally implement the agreements 
reached last September at the White House. I repeat, we need 
courageous people. Mr. Rabin and Mr. Peres are the courageous 
leaders who are making this peace. We are not doing it for our 
or their sake, but for all the people in the region and the 
Middle East, something which will have a positive impact on the 
entire world and on peace throughout the world. I am convinced 
that we are at the end of this long march. Thanks to this hard 
work and our feeling of duty, we will be able to finalize this 
long and difficult process. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Here is Shim'on Peres' statement: 
  [Begin Peres recording, in English with superimposed 
translation into Romanian] I would like to thank Mr. 'Arafat 
and Romania's president for having facilitated this meeting. It 
seems that there is something in Bucharest's air that enables us 
to sit down and calmly talk over the peace process. I know that 
Mr. 'Arafat is leading the Palestinian people toward a new 
destiny, toward something they have never had in the past. We 
wish, from the bottom of our people's heart, that we will be 
successful and that we will see the end of violence, terror, 
death, and suffering. We hope to see the Palestinians as 
neighbors, embarked upon the road of success and prosperity, 
following their historical destiny. As Chairman 'Arafat said, 
we are at the beginning of the end of this process and we are 
trying to find a way to conclude this great historic road of the 
Palestinian and Israeli peoples. This is a new relationship and 
a new beginning. I would like to thank Chairman 'Arafat for the 
attempt he has made, together with us, to end our difficulties. 
We would also like to thank the president for his kind 
hospitality. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

