<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jovanovic Calls Clinton Statement `Unfortunate' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jovanovic Calls Clinton Statement `Unfortunate' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104224794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2234 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104224794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, April 21 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Foreign 
Minister Vladislav Jovanovic said on Thursday [21 April] that 
the latest statement by U.S. President Bill Clinton concerning 
the Bosnian crisis was an escalation of the war of words at the 
very least and could not help put the peace efforts back on the 
negotiation rails. Speaking on Belgrade Radio, Jovanovic 
described Clinton's statement as "unfortunate and unwelcome in 
the extreme." 
  Clinton on Wednesday announced a new U.S. plan for Bosnia- 
Herzegovina, which envisages for massive NATO air strikes 
against Bosnian Serb positions, command points, supply lines and 
warehouses, and a tightening of international sanctions against 
Yugoslavia (Serbia/Montenegro). 
  Jovanovic expressed special concern at the emergence of 
outdated thinking about sanctions as profitable in dealing with 
the crisis in former Yugoslavia, although so far they have been 
counterproductive. 
  The U.N. Security Council has clamped comprehensive and 
mandatory sanctions on Yugoslavia for its alleged involvement in 
the war in neighbouring Bosnia-Herzegovina among the local 
Moslems, Serbs and Croats. 
  "We can only guess at the reasons for the punitive policy 
being pursued blindly and obstinately when it neither benefits 
America nor brings a prospect of ending the Bosnian war and 
establishing peace," Jovanovic said. "We wish to believe that 
this is the last gasp of a policy which has failed, and that the 
latest tough stance towards us will be followed by a more 
rational period in the U.S. policy, which will signal its 
joining the rational forces on which the world can rely in the 
efforts to put the final stop to the Bosnian war," Jovanovic 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9171 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu078_y_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-078 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

