<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akashi Holding Talks With Milosevic, Karadzic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akashi Holding Talks With Milosevic, Karadzic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204112994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1036 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Belgrade, 22 Apr (TANJUG) -- Yasushi Akashi, UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali's special envoy for the 
former Yugoslavia, arrived in Belgrade this morning for a 
meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic and Radovan 
Karadzic, president of the republic of Srpska, immediately upon 
his arrival, we have learned unofficially. The meeting of the 
three in Belgrade is attracting a great deal of attention, 
particularly because of the Gorazde drama and the latest NATO 
threats to the Serbs in Bosnia. Only a few days ago Akashi told 
Butrus-Ghali that he would not talk to Slobodan Milosevic and 
Radovan Karadzic unless, as he said, the attacks on Gorazde were 
to cease and UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] members were to be 
released. 
  Akashi also made his meeting in Belgrade conditional upon a 
total cease-fire in and around Gorazde. At the moment the only 
thing that is certain is the fact that the Serb Republic has 
declared a unilateral cease-fire, so the question now arises as 
to whether this move was sufficient for Akashi to change his 
mind. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

