<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crans Montana Forum -- Meetings, Highlights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crans Montana Forum -- Meetings, Highlights </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Turkey's Cetin Addresses Forum </H4>

<F P=102> AU2204073694 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1730 GMT 21 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204073694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 21/4/1994 -- (Unofficial, 
abridged ROMPRES translation of Turkish Foreign Minister Hikmet 
Cetin) 
  Referring to the fact that the Black Sea is a region in a 
part of the world where conflicts exist, especially in the 
Balkans and in the Caucasus, Hikmet Cetin, minister of foreign 
affairs of Turkey, stressed in his address to the Crans Montana 
Forum proceedings that the interdependence and regional 
collaboration have become more necessary now than ever. He 
highlighted his country played an important role in the 
promotion of a system of cooperation in the Black Sea region, a 
system relying upon economic relations, joint investments, and a 
free trade. 
  Cetin said the purpose of the setting up of the organization 
of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation Zone was rather economic, 
but that did not mean that political difficulties cannot be 
overcome through economic cooperation and development. 
  The organization will develop economic and technological 
cooperation in every domain, but especially in 
telecommunications, transportations, and tourism. 
  The organization was not set up as an alternative to the 
existence of the European Union, but it was rather a step toward 
achieving the European architecture. 

</TEXT>

