<H3> <TI>   Crans Montana Forum -- Meetings, Highlights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crans Montana Forum -- Meetings, Highlights </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Iliescu Speech Praises Peace Efforts </H4>

<F P=102> AU2104180794 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1731 GMT 21 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2104180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 21/4/1993 -- The second plenary 
session of the Crans Montana conference started on Thursday [21 
April] afternoon, on "Economic Perspectives for the Middle East 
in the Aftermath of the Israel-PLO Peace Accord," which had 
President Ion Iliescu as moderator for Romania. 
  The other moderators were: Jean-Paul Carteron, president of 
the Crans Montana Forum Foundation, Yasir 'Arafat, president of 
the Executive Committee of the Palestine Liberation 
Organization, Shim'on Peres, Israeli minister of foreign 
affairs, and Fathi Surur, president of the People's Assembly of 
Egypt. 
  Opening the session, President Ion Iliescu expressed his 
satisfaction at the privilege to be the moderator of the 
discussions of the two politicians who have assumed the 
difficult task to break the deadlock and start negotiations that 
should give shape to peace in the Middle East. Stressing in 
this respect the courage and realistic-mindedness of 'Arafat and 
Peres, President Iliescu highlighted also the contribution of 
Egypt, an important promoter of the peace negotiations in the 
Middle East. He considers that new ways are about to be found 
for the overcoming of the conflict situation, suggesting to the 
international community to back the efforts of the two, who are 
currently under powerful pressure. 
  President Iliescu recalled Minister Peres' saying that one 
would find money more easily for weapons than for building 
peace, and stressed it was the duty of the international 
community to back these two politicians in their constructive 
effort. Also, he hoped the Bucharest meeting would help the 
attainment of the desideratum of peace for which 'Arafat and 
Peres worked. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

