<H3> <TI>   Crans Montana Forum -- Meetings, Highlights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crans Montana Forum -- Meetings, Highlights </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Peres Addresses Forum </H4>

<F P=102> AU2104180894 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1738 GMT 21 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2104180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] bucharest ROMPRES, 21/4/1994 -- In an address on 
Thursday [21 April] to the Crans Montana conference meeting in 
Bucharest, Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres said that his 
meeting with the PLO leader [Yasir 'Arafat] at the Crans Montana 
Forum was not incidental because Bucharest had a peculiar 
significance for Jews and Arabs, as this was the place where 
essential contacts had taken place some years ago on the way of 
building a real peace in the Middle East. 
  The Israeli minister reminded that Israel had recently 
established diplomatic relations with the Vatican and 
appreciated that as an event of the category of those occurring 
once at two thousand years. This model of understanding with 
the Catholic world could be followed by closer relations with 
the Moslem world, said Shim'on Peres. "The historic decision" 
taken by Yasir 'Arafat to negotiate the peace with the Israeli 
was not an easy decision to make in a world dominated by hatred 
and suspicion, said the Israeli foreign minister. 
  Shim'on Peres added that Israel could not afford to remain 
an 
island of prosperity in a sea of poverty because only a new 
standard of living must be the answer to the fundamentalism. 
This is the moment to finalize the peace and not the war, said 
Shim'on Peres, who added further that one could not win through 
battles, but rather through toils in schools. The Israeli 
minister concluded that the "hunting season" was over and it was 
high time that the "creation season" should start. Shim'on 
Peres said he thought the peace bay was near. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

