<H3> <TI>   Slovak Foreign Minister Arrives on Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Slovak Foreign Minister Arrives on Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204074694 Sofia BTA in English 1842 GMT 21 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204074694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 21 (BTA) -- Slovak Foreign Minister 
Eduard Kukan this evening arrived on an official visit to 
Bulgaria. Tomorrow he is expected to meet his Bulgarian 
counterpart Stanislav Daskalov, President Zhelyu Zhelev, 
National Assembly Chairman Aleksandur Yordanov and Deputy Prime 
Minister Evgeni Matinchev. The sides are expected to review the 
legal framework of the bilateral relations. Signing of accords 
is not envisaged. 
  The Bulgarian-Slovak ties date back to the 1939-45 period, 
the time of the first Slovak state. Bulgaria was the sixth 
country to recognize Slovakia after Czechoslovakia was divided 
and immediately after the two countries established diplomatic 
relations in September 1993. According to a Foreign Ministry 
spokesman, the current state of the bilateral relations can be 
described as very good. Experts are now intensively drafting a 
number of economic accords. 
  President Zhelev went to Bratislava during a February 1991 
visit to Czecho-Slovakia. In April 1992 then Slovak prime 
minister Jan Carnogursky paid a formal visit in Sofia. Informal 
meetings between the two parliaments' speakers followed in 1992 
and 1993. Slovak President Michal Kovac last August came to the 
Bulgarian Black Sea coast on a holiday. In the meantime he met 
Bulgarian President Zhelyu Zhelev and invited him to visit 
Slovakia. 
  The Bulgarian-Slovak commercial exchange marks an 
equilibrium 
with figures which are nearly identical in the two directions. 
According to experts, the effected levels are too low and do not 
correspond to the countries' potentials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

