<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Old Payments Account With Slovakia Eliminated </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Old Payments Account With Slovakia Eliminated </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004172394 Prague CTK in English 1645 GMT 20 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2004172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague April 20 (CTK) -- The Czech Government today 
approved a supplement to the payments agreement between the 
Czech Republic and Slovakia eliminating the old account, Deputy 
Premier Josef Lux announced. Payments on the old account of the 
trade payments clearing system served for settling transactions 
concluded between the two countries before the currency division 
on February 8, 1993 and were effected at an exchange rate of one 
Czech to one Slovak crown. Lux added that the government at the 
same time agreed to discuss a new agreement between both 
republics, under which non-government liabilities arisen before 
the currency division would be transferred to the current 
clearing account, used for the payment of liabilities arisen 
after the currency division at the rate valid on February 8, 
1993 -- 34.5 crowns (1.15 USD) to one ECU. State payments from 
the old account would continue to be paid at the one to one 
exchange rate. 
  According to data provided by the Czech Republic, Czech 
companies owed 2 to 3 billion crowns (70-100 million USD) at the 
end of the first quarter and Slovak companies 12 to 14 billion 
crowns (400-460 million USD). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

