<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   LSU: Havel, Klaus Disagree on Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LSU: Havel, Klaus Disagree on Foreign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004155294 Prague CTK in English 1232 GMT 20 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2004155294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague April 20 (CTK) -- A fundamental disagreement 
on foreign policy views was revealed by the absence of the Civic 
Democratic Party (ODS) leaders from the recent Litomysl summit 
of seven presidents, Liberal Social Union [LSU] foreign policy 
secretary and former Czechoslovak Ambassador to Italy Jiri Holub 
told journalists today. Presidents of Austria, the Czech 
Republic, Germany, Hungary, Poland, Slovenia and Slovakia met in 
Litomysl, East Bohemia, on April 15-17. 
  The Czech Republic's image abroad is not helped when the 
invitation to take part in a meeting like that is turned down by 
Premier Vaclav Klaus and Parliament Chairman Milan Uhde, and the 
Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec is not present, Holub said. 
Klaus excused himself on account of preparations for his trip 
to Latin America, Uhde said he was going to a meeting with 
members of the public in Velka Bites, South Moravia, which he 
said he had agreed on seven weeks before, and Zieleniec was 
leaving for Vietnam. Holub said the Realistic Bloc (including 
the Czech Social Democratic Party -- CSSD, the LSU, the 
Christian Social Union -- KSU and the Czech Womens' Union) 
expert group's criticism of the government foreign policy was 
right. 
  "Without the presence of opposition representatives, the 
Foreign Policy Council cannot play its role of coordinating 
foreign policy," Holub said, adding that he was going to ask the 
Presidential Office for an explanation regarding the Litomysl 
meeting circumstances including the presence, or absence, of 
political representatives. 

</TEXT>

