<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Party's Leaders Outline Policy Aims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Party's Leaders Outline Policy Aims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204073494 Prague CTK in English 1711 GMT 21 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204073494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 21 (CTK) -- The Democratic Union 
of Slovakia (DEUS) will support small and medium-sized 
businesses, strive for the acceleration of privatisation, the 
maintenance of microeconomic stability and the speeding up 
restructuring in the Slovak economy, Slovak Deputy Premier Roman 
Kovac said today. 
  Speaking to journalists, Kovac said that DEUS was to be 
founded on April 23 through a merger of the government parties 
Alliance of Democrats (AD) of Milan Knazko and the Alternative 
of Political Realism (APR), the leadership of which includes, 
besides Kovac himself, Premier Jozef Moravcik. 
  Referring to DEUS's programme of economic transformation, 
Knazko said that certain of its principles were in general more 
similar to the Czech variant of transformation than to "what has 
been called economic transformation in the past 21 months 
(during the previous government of Vladimir Meciar, which fell 
in mid-March)". Differences between DEUS's programme and the 
Czech one lie in Slovakia's changed situation after it became 
independent on January 1, 1993, Knazko added. 
  Kovac said that DEUS would stress the right of citizens as 
the only people who can decide on the country's problems. DEUS 
will also strive to secure the economic development in Slovakia, 
as well as the development of the educational level. "A state 
which does not understand how important the education is, loses 
its chance to compete with the advanced world," Kovac said. 
  Reacting to the description of DEUS as a liberal party to 
the 
right of the centre, Kovac said that "there exists one 
millimetre distance to the right of the centre as well". 
  On the forthcoming merger of the AD and the APR, Knazko said 
that "it is a merger following on from certain political 
experiences." He said that the deputies' group of the two 
parties was today joined by a new member. However, he declined 
to give his name. "He will certainly announce it himself," 
Knazko said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

