<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Reveals Increased Support for HZDS </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Reveals Increased Support for HZDS </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204071994 Prague CTK in English 1634 GMT 21 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204071994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava April 21 (CTK) -- Support for the 
Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) has risen by eight 
percent since March, meaning that if elections were held today 
they would win, with 32 percent of the vote, according to a poll 
taken in the first ten days of April by the Slovak Statistical 
Office. 
  Until the middle of March, when the government of HZDS 
Chairman Vladimir Meciar was dismissed, the HZDS was the 
governing party in Slovakia, in coalition with the Slovak 
National Party (SNS). The coalition has now gone into 
opposition. 
  Second would come the Democratic Left Party (SDL) with 13 
percent (14 percent in March) and third the Christian Democratic 
Movement (KDH) with eight percent, as in March. 
  The Egyutteles-Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement 
(MKDH) 
would gain seven percent (nine percent in March) as would 
Premier Jozef Moravcik's Alternative of Political Realism (APR). 
  Parties need five percent of the vote to enter parliament. 
The SNS has gone down from five to four percent, the Democratic 
Party (DS) from four to three percent, and the Green Party of 
Slovakia (SZS) from three to two percent as have the Alliance of 
Democrats (due to merge with the APR this weekend.) 
  Two new parties, Ludovit Cernak's National Democratic 
Party-New Alternative (NDS-NOA) and the Association of Workers 
of Slovakia (SDS) would also win two votes [as received] each. 
  Other parties would only win three percent of the vote 
together, a fairly large fall from last month when they would 
have received 15 percent. The number who do not know what they 
would vote stands at 12 percent, one down from March. 76 
percent say they would definitely or probably take part in 
elections if they were to be held this month, four percent more 
than in March. 
  The results mean that the HZDS-SNS coalition would receive 
36 
percent, the parties of the left-wing, SDL-SDSS-SZS, 18 percent 
and the right-of-centre parties 22 percent. The Hungarian 
minority parties would receive seven percent of the vote. 
  Elections will be held on September 30-October 1. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

