<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Chief of Staff: Serbs Do Not Want War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Chief of Staff: Serbs Do Not Want War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304203294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1847 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304203294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Takovo, Apr 23 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Army Chief of 
Staff Lt. Gen. Momcilo Perisic Saturday [23 April] said that the 
Serb people does not want war, but will not tolerate anyone from 
abroad ordering its life by military threats. Commenting the 
NATO threats to the Serbs in the former Yugoslav Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Perisic ponted out: "I want to believe that 
the latest threats will not be materialized, as their 
consequences could be catastrophic and push the whole Balkan 
region back into prehistory." 
  The NATO council Friday threatened Bosnian Serbs with air 
strikes if they do not withdraw their forces by Sunday at 0001 
GMT to three kilometers away from Gorazde, around which Serb and 
Moslem forces have been fighting bitterly for nearly one month 
since the Moslem forces launched their offensive from this safe 
area on Serb positions in late March. "We will not reply to 
threats by threats, but the Serbian and Montenegrin people must 
not remain indifferent and careless and [word indistinct] their 
state to be destroyed", Perisic said in Takovo at the 
commemoration of the 179th anniversary of the second Serb 
unprising. "We are aware of the great danger looming over all 
Serb lands, but we believe that this can be overcome only by 
just peace", Perisic said, adding that "the [word indistinct] 
weighing over the Serbs' national fate has regretfully received 
illusory legitimacy, and we must all take out fate in our hands, 
determined not to leave it up to others". 
  Commenting the U.N. sanctions against the Federal Republic 
of 
Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.), Perisic said that "the children, the future 
of the nation, are living today in a ghetto set up for them by 
the world powers, which hypocritically explain that peace is 
most easily achieved through the humanitarian isolation of the 
weakest". 
  At the end of May 1992, the U.N. Security Council imposed 
sanctions on the F.R.Y., accusing it of aggression on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, even though there are no Yugoslav army 
troops in that former Yugoslav republic, but its three 
constituent peoples -- Moslems, Serbs and Croats -- are fighting 
in a civil war. 
  "Some world powers are doing all they can to push us to 
civilization's fringes, to subject us to their ill will and 
erase the best pages of our history, thus depriving us of our 
right to the future, but they will not succeed", Perisic said. 
"This is why the unity of the Serb people everywhere is 
necessary now more than ever in order to protect the people from 
the cruelest anti-civilizational isolation", he concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9288 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu079_y_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Duma Delegation Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Duma Delegation Meets With Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204175694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1629 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, April 22 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Prime 
Minister Radoje Kontic said on Friday [22 April] that the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia resolutely urges a political and 
peaceful solution to the crisis in the former Yugoslav Republic 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina and supports Russia's principled and 
objective stand on the crisis in ex-Yugoslav territory. In 
talks with a delegation of the Russian parliament's lower house 
[State Duma], Kontic said that Russia's efforts have prevented 
the escalation of the fighting in Bosnia and underscored that 
the further continuation of the international sanctions against 
Yugoslavia practically prolongs the crisis in the former 
Yugoslav territory. 
  The head of the Russian parliamentary delegation, Nikolay 
Bezbirodov, said that the aim of the visit is to see for 
themselves the situation in Yugoslavia and the developments in 
Bosnia, and thus enable the lower house of the Russian 
parliament to make objective and principled decisions. 
Bezbirodov, who is deputy chairman of the parliamentary Defence 
Committee, said that he lower house is aware that the sanctions 
should be lifted and that they do not contribute to the 
resolution of the crisis in ex-Yugoslav territory. He said that 
the lower house is opposed to the use of military power in the 
settlement of the Bosnian crisis and that all conflicts should 
be resolved through negotiations, in a peaceful way. 
  The Russian delegation also met with the Speaker of the 
Yugoslav Parliament's lower house, Radoman Bozovic, who said 
that peace in Bosnia should be established immediately along the 
separation lines and then that all international institutions 
should be engaged to take part in political talks on all open 
issues. He said that the peace process requires the objective 
and equal treatment of the Serb people, on the same footing as 
all the other warring sides. Pointing out that it is senseless 
to further maintain the sanctions against Yugoslavia, the 
Russian delegation said that a legal project on their lifting 
had been drafted in the lower house, but that the procedure had 
been halted for the present due to the deterioration of the 
situation in Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9289 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu079_y_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic, Akashi, Milosevic Meet in Belgrade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic, Akashi, Milosevic Meet in Belgrade </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Absolute Cease-Fire' Agreement </H4>

<F P=102> LD2204213794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2118 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204213794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 22 Apr (TANJUG) -- The president of the 
Bosnian Serb republic, Radovan Karadzic, and the UN special 
envoy, Yasushi Akashi, and his aides reached an agreement late 
this evening, after almost 10 hours of talks, on an absolute 
cease-fire in the Gorazde area, which is to come into force at 
1000 GMT tomorrow. It was also agreed that the Serbian forces 
would withdraw heavy weapons from Gorazde to a distance from 
which, as Yasushi Akashi said this evening, it would not be 
possible to hit the town. An agreement on the completely free 
movement of humanitarian convoys and the evacuation of the 
wounded from Gorazde was also reached. It has been announced 
that the talks would resume at 0700 GMT tomorrow, with the same 
people attending. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9290 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu079_y_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic, Akashi, Milosevic Meet in Belgrade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic, Akashi, Milosevic Meet in Belgrade </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Talks End With `Success' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2304134894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1243 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2304134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 23 Apr (TANJUG) -- The two-day talks 
between Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, Yasushi Akashi, 
the UN secretary general's special envoy for the former 
Yugoslavia, and Radovan Karadzic, president of the republic of 
Srpska, and their aides ended in Belgrade today with complete 
success. This has been confirmed by the main participants in 
the Belgrade meeting -- Milosevic, Akashi, and Karadzic. In a 
brief statement for journalists after today's second round of 
talks, the Serbian president expressed satisfaction with the 
success of the talks between UN representatives and the republic 
of Srpska. 
  "I believe that a big step has been made toward peace," 
Milosevic said and added: "In the future, the Republic of Serbia 
will continue to lend support to peaceful solutions to the 
Yugoslav crisis through negotiations because we believe that 
this path has no alternative, and it is the only one which leads 
to such a solution." Yasushi Akashi also expressed satisfaction 
with the results of the talks, stressing that "a possibility has 
been created to avoid the crisis." He expressed gratitude to 
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic for the initiative which 
resulted in the two-day meeting in Belgrade. Akashi said that 
he is satisfied with the readiness to cooperate on the part of 
the Bosnian Serb representatives, especially Karadzic. 
  According to Akashi, it was agreed over the past two days 
that the Serbian forces should withdraw to three kilometers from 
the center of Gorazde. "We are planning to deploy peace forces 
around that town as early as this afternoon. I am convinced 
that in that respect we will have full cooperation for the free 
movement of the peace forces on their way to Gorazde before the 
end of the day." 
  Republic of Srpska president Radovan Karadzic's statement 
was 
in the same vein. He said that the Serbian forces will withdraw 
to three kilometers from Gorazde and that relations with the UN 
Protection Force [UNPROFOR] have been fully normalized. If 
there is peace in Gorazde, and peace forces are deployed there, 
that is, if the area is demilitarized and the possibility of a 
Muslim offensive removed, we can hope for a total peace, the 
president of the Serb Republic said in conclusion. 
  The initiative for the two-day meeting in Belgrade was 
launched by Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, who based it 
on the firm conviction that the crisis can be solved through 
negotiations and not through escalation of the war. Milosevic 
suggested that the representatiaves of the United Nations and of 
the republic of Srpska should discuss three issues: the 
normalization of relations between the republic of Srpska and 
UNPROFOR, an end to the conflict around Gorazde, and an 
agreement on a cessation of hostilities throughout the territory 
of former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Milosevic's proposal was accepted and a full accord was 
reached on six issues. There is no doubt that the most 
important agreement is the one on the immediate and total 
cease-fire in and around Gorazde. Under the agreement, the 
cease-fire was to come into force at noon today. The agreement 
on the normalization of relations between the republic of Srpska 
and UNPROFOR is also of great importance, as well as the 
consensus that an agreement on a cease-fire throughout the 
territory of former Bosnia-Herzegovina must be reached. 
  The question now is: Whose turn is it to make a move after 
the Belgrade agreement? Everything indicates that the 
conclusion is that it is the Bosnian Muslims. The wish of only 
one side is not enough for a cease-fire, nor is it enough for a 
war. In a certain way, NATO made a move out of turn by issuing 
fresh threats and ultimatums, and only to one side -- the 
Serbian side. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9291 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu079_y_94007" </HT>


